{readme}
# T.I.M

A Markdown-inspired markup language built around deterministic parsing and explicit document structure.

---

## Why?

Markdown is excellent for writing, but modern documents often need more structure than traditional Markdown can express without embedded HTML.

T.I.M extends the familiar syntax with first-class document structures while keeping the source clean and readable.

::note

The goal of T.I.M is not to replace Markdown.

Instead, it provides a well-defined grammar for authors and compiler developers who want predictable parsing and structured document trees.

::

---

## Features

{feature-list}

- Headers
- Paragraphs
- Horizontal rules
- Ordered lists
- Unordered lists
- Nested lists
- Code blocks
- Inline code
- Links
- Images
- IDs
- Classes
- Note blocks

---

## Attributes

Attributes are declared on the line immediately before the block they apply to.

{hero, centered, dark}
### Styled Header

This header has the ID `hero` and the classes `centered` and `dark`.

{_, warning, rounded}
This paragraph has no ID, but it has two classes.

---

## Lists

### Unordered

- First item
- Second item
- Third item
    - Nested item
    - Another nested item

### Ordered

1. Install T.I.M
2. Write a document
3. Parse the document
4. Render the output

---

## Notes

::note

This is a note block.

It can contain multiple paragraphs.

- Lists
- Headers
- Other block elements

### Inside the note

Everything inside belongs to the note until the closing delimiter.

::

---

## Code

Inline code looks like `cargo run`.

Code blocks support language identifiers.

``rust
fn main() {
    println!("Hello from T.I.M!");
}
``

``text
This is plain text.

Nothing inside here should be parsed as markup.

- Not a list
# Not a heading
``

